# .doc-reference-ignore — paths exempted from validate-doc-references.sh
# (one regex per line, matched against the resolved project-relative path and
# the raw link target; '#' starts a comment)
#
# Tula renders on GitHub.com, not GitBook. The validator additionally flags
# targets that resolve on GitHub but are fragile on GitBook (bare extensionless
# files; trailing-slash directory targets). The entries below are GitHub-valid
# links we intentionally keep — they are NOT broken; they are GitBook-only
# fragilities that do not apply to this repo's render target. Genuinely broken
# links (missing files, wrong relative paths) are deliberately NOT listed here
# so the validator still catches them.

# Root license/notice files (bare, extensionless — idiomatic GitHub root links).
# Covers root README/TRADEMARK and skills/health-records/ (which ships its own LICENSE).
^LICENSE$
^NOTICE$

# Directory targets — GitHub renders the folder (and its README/SKILL); the
# link points at a real directory deliberately. Anchored so only these exact
# dirs are exempt (a broken link elsewhere still fails).
^evals/?$
^scripts/?$
^skills/med-pdf/?$
^skills/epic-note/?$
^skills/health-records/?$
^skills/myhealth-pulse/?$
^skills/memory-diff/?$
^apps/my-aria/?$
^scripts/email-smoke-test/?$

# CI-generated status doc — produced by .github/workflows/eval-status.yml on
# main, not committed to the tree, so it resolves only post-CI. Referenced from
# README.md and OPEN_CORE.md.
^docs/evals\.md$

# Canonical articles (articles/*.md) are maintainer-authored content carried
# from the origin repo; their internal links are upstream's to maintain and are
# out of scope for this consumer's CI. The targets below are the relative-link
# forms used inside articles/i-built-the-patient-portal-my-agent-deserves.md.
^articles/i-gave-an-ai-agent-oauth-access-to-my-hospital\.md$
^apps/my-aria/public/my-aria-dashboard\.png$
^apps/my-aria/public/my-aria-ai-chats\.png$
^apps/my-aria/public/my-aria-home-devices\.png$
